gmx:name.gco:CharacterString: Feature catalog for United States National Atlas Public Land Survey, 1972-2002

gmx:scope.gco:CharacterString: Land use surveys; Public lands; Indian reservations; Military reservations; Land grants

gfc:definition.gco:CharacterString: The polygons represent the Public Land Survey which is a rectangular system of surveys devised to subdivide public domain lands within United States; in addition are donation land claims, Indian lands, land grants, civil colonies, military reservations, overlapping land grants, private surveys, unsurveyed areas, and areas not part of the Public Land Survey System within United States.
Internal feature number.
Feature geometry.

gmd:title.gco:CharacterString: National Atlas of the United States and the United States Geological Survey

gmd:organisationName.gco:CharacterString: National Atlas of the United States and the United States Geological Survey

gfc:definition.gco:CharacterString: An area that was allocated to a settler under the Donation Act of September 27, 1850 to preserve the rights of pre-statehood settlers claimed prior to the regular division of townships and ranges.
Land granted to native Americans and excluded from the public domain.
An area of land to which title was conferred by a predecessor government and confirmed by the U.S. Government after the territory in which it is situated was acquired by the United States.
A military or lighthouse reservation that limits the public lands.

gfc:label.gco:CharacterString: Not Part of Public Land Surveys System

gfc:definition.gco:CharacterString: An area that is outside of the Public Land Survey System.

An area of land to which more than one title was conferred by a predecessor government and confirmed by the U.S. Government after the territory in which it is situated was acquired by the United States. These areas are the result of survey error or disputed claims.
An area of private surveys of public domain lands.

An area of land subdivided by the Public Land Survey System (PLSS), which was originally created on public domain lands and the rules for its use were defined by the authority of the U.S. Government. The PLSS has since been extended, following similar rules, into non- public domain areas.
An area that is part of the public domain but which has not been subdivided.
Areas of navigable streams and meanderable lakes which are excluded from the Public Land Survey System.
The township and range designation for the area.
